<p><a name="Imperfect_tense" id="Imperfect_tense"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_conjugation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Imperfect tense">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Imperfect tense</span></h3>
<p>The imperfect tense (Latin <i>tempus imperfectum</i>) indicates a perpetual, but incomplete action in the past. It is recognized by the tense signs <i>bǎ</i> and <i>bā</i> in the indicative, and <i>re</i> and <i>rē</i> in the subjunctive.</p>
<p><a name="Indicative_imperfect" id="Indicative_imperfect"></a></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_conjugation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Indicative imperfect">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Indicative imperfect</span></h4>
<p>In the indicative mood, the imperfect simply express an action in the past that was not completed. <i>Portābam</i> can be translated to mean, "I was carrying," "I kept carrying," or "I used to carry."</p>
<ul>
<li>In the indicative, the imperfect employs its tense signs <i>ba</i> and <i>bā</i> before personal endings are added.</li>
</ul>
<table class="wikitable">
<tr bgcolor="#EFEFEF">
<th rowspan="3"></th>
<th colspan="8"><b>Indicative Active Imperfect</b></th>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#EFEFEF">
