<p><a name="Pluperfect_tense" id="Pluperfect_tense"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_conjugation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Pluperfect tense">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Pluperfect tense</span></h3>
<p>The pluperfect tense (Latin <i>tempus plūs quam perfectum</i>) expresses an action which was completed before another completed action. It is recognized by the tense signs <i>era</i> and <i>erā</i> in the indicative and <i>isse</i> and <i>issē</i> in the subjunctive.</p>
<p><a name="Indicative_pluperfect" id="Indicative_pluperfect"></a></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_conjugation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: Indicative pluperfect">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Indicative pluperfect</span></h4>
<p>As with English, in Latin, the indicative pluperfect is used to assert an action that was completed before another (perfect tense). <i>Portāveram</i> translates as "I had carried."</p>
<ul>
<li>The tense sign <i>erā</i> is employed before adding the personal endings, with the long ā following the usual rules for shortening before final -m, -t, and -nt.</li>
</ul>
<table class="wikitable">
<tr bgcolor="#EFEFEF">
