<p><a name="The_supine" id="The_supine"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Latin_conjugation&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: The supine">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">The supine</span></h3>
<div class="rellink boilerplate seealso">See also: <a href="/wiki/Supine" title="Supine">Supine</a></div>
<p>The supine is the fourth principal part. It resembles a masculine noun of the <a href="/wiki/Latin_declension#Fourth_declension_.28u.29" title="Latin declension">fourth declension</a>. Supines only occur in the accusative and ablative cases.</p>
<ul>
<li>The accusative form ends in a <i>–um</i>, and is used with a verb of motion in order to show the purpose. Thus, it is only used with verbs like <i>cedere</i>, <i>venīre</i>, etc. The accusative form of a supine can also take an object if needed.
<ul>
<li><i>Pater vēnit <b>portātum</b> līberōs suōs.</i> — The father came to carry his children.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>The ablative, which ends in a <i>–ū</i>, is used with the Ablative of Specification.
<ul>
<li><i>Arma haec facillima <b>portātū</b> erant.</i> — These arms were the easiest to carry.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<table class="wikitable">
<tr bgcolor="#EFEFEF">
<th rowspan="2"></th>
<th colspan="5"><b>Supine</b></th>
</tr>
<tr bgcolor="#EFEFEF">
<th colspan="1"><b>portāre</b></th>
<th colspan="1"><b>terrēre</b></th>
<th colspan="1"><b>petere</b></th>
<th colspan="1"><b>audīre</b></th>
</tr>
<tr>
